  <div class="container">
    <div class="article-page__body">
      <div class="article-page__content rte">
        <p>The most common layering mistake is reaching for one very thick piece instead of several thinner ones. Layers trap warm air between them, and each layer can be added or removed as the temperature (or your activity level) changes — a single heavy coat can't do that.</p>

        <h2>The three-layer system</h2>
        <h3>1. Base layer — manages moisture</h3>
        <p>Sits against your skin and moves sweat away from your body. Merino wool and synthetic base layers both work well; cotton does not, since it holds moisture against your skin and cools you down once you stop moving.</p>

        <h3>2. Mid layer — traps warmth</h3>
        <p>Fleece, wool sweaters, or a lightweight puffer create the insulating air pockets that actually keep you warm. This is the layer to adjust first: swap a thin fleece for a heavier one as it gets colder, rather than jumping straight to your heaviest coat.</p>

        <h3>3. Shell layer — blocks wind and water</h3>
        <p>Your jacket's outer shell protects the insulation underneath from wind and precipitation. A shell that's too tight compresses your mid layer and reduces its warmth — size your outer jacket to comfortably fit over what's underneath it.</p>

        <h2>Avoiding the "marshmallow" look</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Choose slimmer mid layers (merino or technical fleece) instead of a second puffer — bulk comes from stacking loose, thick fabrics, not from the number of layers.</li>
          <li>Tuck your base layer in and keep your mid layer close-fitting; let only your outer shell have room to move.</li>
          <li>Pick one statement layer (usually the shell) and keep the others simple in color and cut.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Adjusting on the go</h2>
        <p>Layering's biggest advantage is flexibility. Heading indoors after a cold commute? Lose the shell first — it's doing the least to regulate your temperature once you're out of the wind. Stepping back outside? Shell goes back on before you add another mid layer; wind protection usually matters more than extra insulation.</p>

        <h2>Matching layers to your jacket</h2>
        <p>If your outer jacket already has a warm liner (like our shearling or quilted styles), you likely only need a base and light mid layer underneath. Lighter shells — bombers, denim, or unlined trenches — depend more on what you layer underneath them for warmth.</p>

        <p>Not sure which shell fits your layering style? Compare options in our <a href="/pages/journal-jacket-types-guide">jacket types guide</a>, or browse the <a href="/collections/all">full collection</a> to find your outer layer.</p>
